**2.3 End User Passwords**

An end user account is an account used by a person to access resources such as workstations and web applications without elevated access.

Impose appropriate complexity, aging, account lockout, and password history controls for end user passwords.

| C# | Control Statement | LOW | MOD | HIGH |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 2.3.1 | End user account passwords must contain characters from at least three of the following four categories:      Lower case alpha (a  z)  Upper case alpha (A  Z)  Number (0  9)  Non- | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.2 | End user account passwords must have a minimum length of 10 characters. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.3 | End user passwords must be changed at least once every 60 days. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.4 | End user passwords should automatically expire if not changed within 60 days. | Should | Should | Should |
| 2.3.5 | Expired passwords for end user accounts must trigger a forced password change upon next sign in. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.6 | End user accounts must be automatically locked after 15 failed login attempts. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.7 | End user accounts automatically locked for failed login attempts must be automatically unlocked after 30 minutes. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.8 | The root cause of account lockouts for end user accounts should be investigated and documented when the account lockout occurs more than 10 times within a 24 hour period. | Should | Should | Should |
| 2.3.9 | End user accounts must have the password history count set to 24 or a greater value. | Must | Must | Must |
| 2.3.10 | Generic, shared or pooled end user accounts must not be created or used. | Must | Must | Must |
